{"title_page": "Hurtigruten", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n[[File:MS Trollfjord snur.jpg|thumb|{{MS|Trollfjord||6}}, in service since 2010, in [[Molde]]]]\n\n'''Hurtigruten''' (\"Express Route\", formally The coastal route Bergen-Kirkenes) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] public coastal route transporting passengers that travel locally, regionally and between the ports of call, and also cargo between ports north of [[Troms\u00f8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regjeringen.no/en/topics/transport-and-communications/kollektivtransport/the-coastal-route-bergen-kirkenes/id2517170/|title=The coastal route Bergen-Kirkenes|last=Communications|first=Ministry of Transport and|date=2016-12-16|website=Government.no|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nHurtigruten provides daily, year-round and consistent traffic between [[Bergen]] and [[Kirkenes]] with 34 ports of call on northbound and 33 ports of call on southbound sailings. The Ministry of Transport and Communications in Norway has set minimum capacity requirements of 320 passengers, 120 berths and cargo for 150 Euro-pallets. The current agreement with the privately held company [[Hurtigruten AS]] entered into force on 1 January 2012 and expired on 31 December 2019, with an optional 1-year extension. From 2021 the two companies Hurtigruten AS and [[Havila Kystruten]] AS will operate the route.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regjeringen.no/no/tema/transport-og-kommunikasjon/kollektivtransport/kystruten/id2517170/|title=Kystruten Bergen-Kirkenes|last=Samferdselsdepartementet|date=2016-12-15|website=Regjeringen.no|language=no|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:DS Vesteraalen fra siden.jpg|thumb|{{SS|Vesteraalen|1890|2}} near [[Bod\u00f8]] on her first round-trip in 1893.]]\n\nHurtigruten was established in 1893{{Fix|text=under what name?}} by government contract to improve communications along Norway's long, jagged coastline. {{SS|Vesteraalen|1890|2}} began the first round-trip journey from Trondheim on 2 July 1893 bound for [[Hammerfest (town)|Hammerfest]], with calls at [[R\u00f8rvik]], [[Br\u00f8nn\u00f8y]], [[Sandnessj\u00f8en]], [[Bod\u00f8]], [[Svolv\u00e6r]], [[L\u00f8dingen]], [[Harstad]], [[Troms\u00f8]] and [[Skjerv\u00f8y]]. The ship arrived at Svolv\u00e6r on Monday 3 July at 8pm after 35\u00bd hours and at Hammerfest on Wednesday 5 July after 67 hours. She was commanded by Hurtigruten founder [[Richard With]]. As of 2008, the Trondheim\u2013Svolv\u00e6r trip took 33 hours and the Trondheim\u2013Hammerfest trip took 41 hours 15 min.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nBefore Hurtigruten opened, only [[Vesteraalens Dampskibsselskab]] was willing to make the trip through the then poorly-charted waters; the voyage was especially difficult during the long, dark winters. Hurtigruten was a substantial breakthrough for communities along its path. Mail from central Norway to Hammerfest, which used to take three weeks in summer and five months in winter, could now be delivered in seven days.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:MS Narvik in Svolvaer.jpg|thumb|left|The 1982-built [[MS Narvik (1982)|''Narvik'']] in [[Svolv\u00e6r]]. The ship was sold in 2007.]]\n\nEncouraged by Vesteraalens' early success, several other shipping companies obtained a concession to operate the route, extended to run between Bergen in the southwest and Kirkenes in the far northeast. A fleet of 11 ships visits each of the 34 ports daily, both northbound and southbound.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nUntil the 1940s most ports north of Trondheim could not be reached by road from Oslo, so the sea was the only means of access. Beginning in the 1960s, the role of Hurtigruten changed, in part because of the construction of a local airport network and road improvements. Operating subsidies were gradually phased out, and the operators put more emphasis on tourism. New, bigger and more luxurious ships were introduced in the 1980s, with attention given to hot tubs, bars, restaurants and other comforts. However, Hurtigruten still serves important passenger and cargo needs, and operates 365 days a year. The last two independent shipping companies, [[Ofotens og Vesteraalens Dampskibsselskab]] (OVDS) and [[Troms Fylkes Dampskibsselskap]] (TFDS), merged on 1 March 2006 as the [[Hurtigruten Group]], a year later becoming Hurtigruten ASA. In 2015 Hurtigruten was delisted from the Oslo stock exchange after the company was acquired by the private equity group [[TDR Capital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=tdrcapital.com|url=http://www.tdrcapital.com/hurtigruten|website=tdrcapital.com|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-26/cruise-operator-hurtigruten-said-to-attract-private-equity-firms|title=Cruise Operator Hurtigruten Said to Attract Private Equity Firms|last1=Syed|first1=Sara|last2=Porter|first2=Kiel|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=28 March 2017}}</ref> In addition to the voyages in Norway, the company operates expedition cruises to Greenland, Canada, South America, Iceland, Svalbard and Antarctica.\n\n{{-}}\n\n==New contracts==\nThe Ministry of Transport and Communications in Norway announced in 2017 that the Hurtigruten contract was split into three contracts. The contracts were put up for bid and in the end, two were granted to Hurtigruten AS and one to Havila Kystruten AS, with each operating seven and four ships respectively. The two companies will alternate departure days for the entire route from Bergen to Kirkenes.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsinenglish.no/2018/03/23/hurtigruten-gets-new-coastal-rival/|title=Hurtigruten gets new coastal rival|website=www.newsinenglish.no|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nHavila Kystruten AS is building four new vessels to serve the route, while Hurtigruten AS will be refitting seven of its vessels to meet the stricter emissions requirements.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe four new vessels from Havila will run on LNG and battery power. LNG will cut CO\u2082 emissions by 25 per cent, and the battery power will yield additional savings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theexplorer.no/solutions/hybrid-cruiseliners-cut-coastal-emissions/|title=Hybrid cruiseliners cut coastal emissions|website=www.theexplorer.no|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> The vessels will be named Havila Capella, Havila Castor, Havila Polaris and Havila Pollux. All four vessels is under construction at Tersan shipyard in Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cruiseandferry.net/articles/tersan-shipyard-to-build-two-ships-for-havila-kystruten-1|title=Tersan Shipyard to build two ships for Havila Kystruten|website=CruiseandFerry.net|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nExisting vessels from Hurtigruten will be modernized and renovated in order to meet the new requirements.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[MS Midnatsol (2002)|MS Eirik Raude]], [[MS Trollfjord]] and [[MS Finnmarken (2002)|MS Otto Sverdrup]] are all getting modernized and renovated with a scandinavian interior style similar to the expedition vessels [[MS Roald Amundsen]] and [[MS Fridtjof Nansen]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe ships will be fitted with filters and LNG compatible engines in order to reduce emissions by 25%. The ships will also get hybrid motors, and battery packs.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Current fleet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.no/praktisk-informasjon/ruteplan/|title=Current Route Plan|last=|first=|date=|website=www.hurtigruten.no|language=no|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ==\n[[File:MS Nordlys in Hammerfest.jpg|thumb|{{MS|Nordlys|1993|6}} at [[Hammerfest (town)|Hammerfest]] in June 2005, displaying the TFDS funnel colours.]]\n[[File:MS Richard With vor den Lofoten.jpg|thumb|{{MS|Richard With||6}} between [[Svolv\u00e6r]] and [[Kabelv\u00e5g]]]][[MS Midnatsol (2002)|MS Eirik Raude]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-eirik-raude/|title=MS Eirik Raude|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Trollfjord]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-trollfjord/|title=MS Trollfjord|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> (Will be renamed MS Maud)\n\n[[MS Nordlys (1994)|MS Nordlys]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-nordlys/|title=MS Nordlys|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Finnmarken (2002)|MS Otto Sverdrup]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-otto-sverdrup/|title=MS Otto Sverdrup|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Vester\u00e5len]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.no/skip/ms-vesteralen/|title=MS Vester\u00e5len|website=www.hurtigruten.no|language=no|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Kong Harald]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-kong-harald/|title=MS Kong Harald|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Nordnorge (1997)|MS Nordnorge]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-nordnorge/|title=MS Nordnorge|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Polarlys (1995)|MS Polarlys]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-polarlys/|title=MS Polarlys|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Spitsbergen]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-spitsbergen/|title=MS Spitsbergen|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Lofoten]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.no/skip/ms-lofoten/|title=MS Lofoten|website=www.hurtigruten.no|language=no|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Nordkapp]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/our-ships/ms-nordkapp/|title=MS Nordkapp|website=www.hurtigruten.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[MS Richard With]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurtigruten.no/skip/ms-richard-with/|title=MS Richard With|website=www.hurtigruten.no|language=no|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:MS Nordstjernen in Bergen.jpg|thumb|{{MS|Nordstjernen||6}} in Bergen]]\n\n==Places visited on coastal route==\nIn order, northbound:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Bergen]]\n* [[Flor\u00f8]]\n* [[M\u00e5l\u00f8y]]\n* [[Her\u00f8y, M\u00f8re og Romsdal|Torvik]]\n* [[\u00c5lesund]]\n* [[Geiranger]] (''summer only'')\n* [[Urke, M\u00f8re og Romsdal]] (''September & October only'')\n* [[Molde]]\n* [[Kristiansund]]\n* [[Trondheim]]\n* [[R\u00f8rvik]]\n* [[Br\u00f8nn\u00f8ysund]]\n* [[Sandnessj\u00f8en]]\n* [[Nesna]]\n* [[\u00d8rnes]]\n* [[Bod\u00f8]]\n* [[Stamsund]]\n* [[Svolv\u00e6r]]\n* [[Stokmarknes]]\n* [[Sortland]]\n* [[Ris\u00f8yhamn]]\n* [[Harstad (town)|Harstad]] ({{coord|68|47|57|N|16|32|54|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Finnsnes]] ({{coord|69|13|44|N|17|58|25|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Troms\u00f8]] ({{coord|69|38|54|N|18|57|45|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Skjerv\u00f8y (village)|Skjerv\u00f8y]] ({{coord|70|2|6|N|20|58|57|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[\u00d8ksfjord]] ({{coord|70|14|14|N|22|20|55|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Hammerfest (town)|Hammerfest]] ({{coord|70|39|53|N|23|40|51|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Hav\u00f8ysund]] ({{coord|70|59|42|N|24|41|14|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Honningsv\u00e5g]] ({{coord|70|58|51|N|25|58|7|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Kj\u00f8llefjord]] ({{coord|70|56|58|N|27|19|54|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Mehamn]]\n* [[Berlev\u00e5g (village)|Berlev\u00e5g]] ({{coord|70|51|26|N|29|6|54|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[B\u00e5tsfjord (village)|B\u00e5tsfjord]] ({{coord|70|37|46|N|29|43|21|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Vard\u00f8 (town)|Vard\u00f8]] ({{coord|70|22|27|N|31|6|16|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Vads\u00f8 (town)|Vads\u00f8]] ({{coord|70|4|14|N|29|44|10|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n* [[Kirkenes]] ({{coord|69|43|43|N|30|4|19|E|display=inline|region:NO_type:landmark}})\n}}\n\n==Live television broadcast==\n{{see also|Slow television#2011: Hurtigruten \u2013 minutt for minutt}}\n\nAs part of its [[slow television]] series, the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] transmitted non-stop the Hurtigruten ship {{MS|Nordnorge|1996|6}}'s 134-hour voyage from [[Bergen]] to [[Kirkenes]], which started on June 16, 2011.<ref name=\"NRK Beta\">{{cite web|last=Hofseth|first=Anders|title=Hurtigruten: 5 day TV marathon in the midnight sun|website=NRK|date=16 June 2011|url=https://nrkbeta.no/2011/06/16/hurtigruten-eng/}}</ref>\n\n==Post-World War II accidents and incidents==\n[[File:Memorial 1958 MS Earling Jarl.jpg|thumb|Memorial in [[Bod\u00f8]] commemorating the incident on board ''Erling Jarl'' in 1958. Total height: 2,3 meters. Sculptor: [[Istvan Lisztes]].]]\n\nBefore World War II, a number of ships perished, usually because they ran aground in bad visibility.\n\nMost of the Hurtigruten fleet was sunk during World War II.\n\nIn September 1954 {{SS|Nordstjernen|1937|6}} ran aground in [[Raftsundet]] at night. The ship started taking on water and sank. Five persons died. There were 157 passengers and a crew of 46 on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vol.no/nyheter/article409004.ece|author=Rydheim, Per|title=D/S Nordstjernen|website=Vol.no|date=28 November 2010|access-date=28 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurtigrutemuseet.no/nb/ulykkerogforlis|title=Ulykker og forlis|language=Norwegian|trans-title=Accidents and shipwrecks|website=Hurtigrutemuseet|access-date=28 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130222195030/http://www.hurtigrutemuseet.no/nb/ulykkerogforlis|archivedate=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 1958, a fire broke out on board MS ''Erling Jarl'' while the vessel was docked at [[Bod\u00f8]]. Due to the thick smoke 14 people died of smoke inhalation. Today a memorial to the incident stands at Bod\u00f8.<ref>{{cite web|title=History Erling Jarl (1949)|url=http://hurtigrutemuseet.no/nb/historien-erling-jarl-1949|website=The Virtual Museum of Hurtigruten|access-date=9 October 2016}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Elling Finnanger Sn\u00f8fugl|title=Klart for minnesmerke|url=https://www.an.no/nyheter/klart-for-minnesmerke/s/1-33-4218481|website=Avisa nordland|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 1962 MS ''Sanct Svithun'' ran onto a reef in the maritime area [[Folda, Nord-Tr\u00f8ndelag|Folda]] in [[Nord-Tr\u00f8ndelag]] because of a major navigational error after leaving [[Trondheim]]. Of 89 persons on board (passengers, crew and two postal officers) 41 died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurtigrutemuseet.no/nb/sanctsvithun|title=Historien Sanct Svithun|language=Norwegian|trans-title=History of Sanct Svithun|website=Hurtigrutemuseet|access-date=28 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107120130/http://www.hurtigrutemuseet.no/nb/sanctsvithun|archive-date=7 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 {{MS|Nordlys|1993|6}} suffered an engine room fire, leading to two deaths among the crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dagbladet.no/2011/09/15/nyheter/hurtigruten/innenriks/brann/18144200/|author1=Torgeir P. Krokfjord |last2=Barstein |first2=Geir |last3=Walderhaug |first3=Fridgeir |title=To bekreftet omkommet etter brann p\u00e5 hurtigruta|language=Norwegian|trans-title=Two confirmed dead after fire on Hurtigruten|website=Dagbladet|date=15 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book|l